The Problem

The file interface has remained relatively stagnant over the last 50 years. It's an array of bytes where you can read and write data. Every language, runtime, and storage stack builds on this model — and high-performance systems often hit crucial reliability and fault tolerance walls when it comes down to the fact that file reads and writes are not atomic. fwrite doesn't guarantee bytes hit disk. A crash mid-write leaves your file in an unknown, unrecoverable state. And if you need to insert bytes in the middle of a large file, you're rewriting everything downstream. These are fundamental limitations of the file primitive itself.

What Smart Files Does

Smart Files is an application-level database engine that acts like the file model with the guarantees we already expect from high-performance databases, applied at the granularity of a single file. This talk walks through the design and implementation of four core capabilities:

- Crash-safe writes via a write-ahead log — every write commits fully or rolls back cleanly, no partial state, no corruption window.
- O(log N) inner mutations — insert or remove bytes anywhere in the stream without rewriting the tail.
- Stride access — read, write, and remove at regular intervals without manual offset arithmetic or wrapper logic.
- Multiple named streams per file — no separate file handles, no embedded SQLite, no format hacks.


